Crime Master Putin
Moscow — German, French, and Swedish medical experts have unanimously stated: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the anti-corruption foundation.
Fortunately, because Navalny survived, the relationship between Russia and Germany does not deteriorate.
To show his "clear position," German Chancellor Merkel announced: Navalny is a "victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to launch an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation's results prove that the Russian government is the culprit, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Nevertheless, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political enemies.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted, "There is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, head of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, even said it was an act by Western intelligence agencies, thereby damaging the credibility of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly unreasonable, but he also pointed out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
It is unacceptable to poison a well-known political opponent just before an upcoming election, especially using a toxin developed by the former Soviet Union.
Furthermore, the timing is particularly intriguing, especially with Belarusian citizens protesting against the August elections.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was especially confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If it was indeed the Russian government as Germany claims, this assassination was a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics (the number one rebel figure in the movie Star Wars), interfering in the US election, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK out of the EU, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny flee to Germany, and be diagnosed as poisoned so quickly?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline to Germany is facing cancellation.
This assassination clearly backfired.
In fact, it has further fueled public opposition to the misconduct of the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, the claim that it was Western intelligence agencies is even more exaggerated.
If such allegations are true, German and Swedish scientists would not have disclosed the fact about the nerve agent Novichok.
It is more likely a conspiracy planned by Putin's political circle.
Perhaps Putin wanted Navalny to shut up before the big election, or maybe it was due to his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Although Putin's political enforcers are loyal but very foolish, they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few participants knew the truth.
Other failed poisoning operations have similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the public investigation committee of Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning of Peter Verkhilov, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on the abuse of justice in Russia.
It can be traced back even further to 2006, when the former KGB Alexander Litvinenko was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko often criticized Russia's security agencies.
As with the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was shot dead two years later in an elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death caused immense damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin at all.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, and it is a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is exactly what the Kremlin wanted. Making the master Putin happy is the ultimate goal of the henchmen.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning fails, they will not be punished.
Because they did it for the president's interests.
Those who want to find proof of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless, the Kremlin is the real culprit.
Western countries must clearly state their position, even if their own economy is affected, they should take sanctions against Russia.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that occur in Russia are attributed to himself.
